  {# ── 4. ISR ── #}
  <h3>4. Incremental Static Regeneration (ISR)</h3>
  <p>
    ISR extends Static Site Generation (SSG) by allowing pages to be updated in the background after deployment, enabling static performance with fresher data.
  </p>

  <h4>How it works</h4>
  <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">Combines static performance with periodic updates</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Pages are regenerated in the background while serving existing content</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Suitable for content that changes occasionally</li>
  </ul>

  <h4>Pros</h4>
  <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">Static performance with updated data</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Low JavaScript overhead</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Strong caching</li>
  </ul>

  <h4>Cons</h4>
  <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">More architectural complexity</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Edge cases during regeneration</li>
  </ul>

  <h4>LRO guidance</h4>
  <p><strong>LRO guidance: </strong>Well-suited for content that changes occasionally, while retaining the benefits of static delivery.</p>


  {# ── 5. Progressive Enhancement ── #}
  <h3>5. Progressive Enhancement</h3>
  <p>Building frontends that work without JavaScript, then enhancing with interactive features.</p>

  <p><em><a class="vf-link" href="/web-optimisation-framework/principles/progressive-enhancement/">Read more</a></em></p>


